---
import LabLayout from '../../layouts/LabLayout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<LabLayout title="Lab 3: Keypad Scanner" labNum={3} githubUrl="https://github.com/juliacygong/E155/tree/main/lab03">
  <section>
    <h2>Introduction</h2>
    <p>
      The purpose of this lab was to debounce signals from key presses on a 4×4 keyboard. The last two inputs
      pressed are displayed on a dual 7-segment display. The display does not lock up if multiple keys are
      pressed simultaneously, and ignores other inputs when one key is held down.
    </p>

    <h2>FPGA Design and Testing Methodology</h2>
    <p>
      I designed an FSM to debounce the keyboard properly. This lab focused on synchronous sequential logic —
      synchronizing column inputs and tracking what clock cycles specific values update at.
    </p>
    <p>
      The dual 7-segment display from Lab 2 was reused (same clock divider, hardware layout, and submodules).
    </p>

    <h3>Hardware Implementation</h3>
    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}images/labs/lab3/lab3_board.jpg`} alt="Breadboard layout" />
      <figcaption>Figure 1: Breadboard layout of the dual 7-segment display with the 4×4 keyboard.</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Components: development board, 4×4 keypad, dual 7-segment display, two 2N3906 PNP transistors.
    </p>
    <p>
      Current-limiting resistors for keypad pins: V = 3.3V, I = 8mA → R = 410Ω. Used 510Ω resistors.
    </p>

    <h2>Technical Documentation</h2>
    <p>
      Source code in <a href="https://github.com/juliacygong/E155/tree/main/lab03" target="_blank" rel="noopener">GitHub</a>:
      top module, all submodules, and testbenches.
    </p>

    <h3>FSM Design</h3>
    <p>
      I chose FSM + counters over hardware RC circuits (more flexible, tunable in code) and over shift-register
      oversampling (fewer flip-flops, integrates naturally with the keypad state machine). The tradeoff: very brief
      taps shorter than the debounce window may be missed — acceptable for human inputs.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}images/labs/lab3/lab3_fsm.png`} alt="FSM diagram" />
      <figcaption>Figure 2: FSM used to debounce key inputs (6 states).</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h3>FSM State Transition Table</h3>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Current State</th>
          <th>Input Condition</th>
          <th>Next State</th>
          <th>Outputs (row_stop, key_valid, reset_count)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>WAIT</td><td>key_col != 0 &amp;&amp; one-hot &amp;&amp; key_val[7:4] != 0</td><td>INPUT</td><td>1, 0, 0</td></tr>
        <tr><td>WAIT</td><td>otherwise</td><td>WAIT</td><td>0, 0, 0</td></tr>
        <tr><td>INPUT</td><td>(always)</td><td>INPUT_WAIT</td><td>1, 0, 0</td></tr>
        <tr><td>INPUT_WAIT</td><td>counter[2] == 1</td><td>HOLD</td><td>1, 1, 1</td></tr>
        <tr><td>INPUT_WAIT</td><td>otherwise</td><td>INPUT_WAIT</td><td>1, 0, 1</td></tr>
        <tr><td>HOLD</td><td>key_col == 0</td><td>DEBOUNCE</td><td>1, 0, 0</td></tr>
        <tr><td>HOLD</td><td>otherwise</td><td>HOLD</td><td>1, 0, 0</td></tr>
        <tr><td>DEBOUNCE</td><td>(always)</td><td>DEBOUNCE_WAIT</td><td>1, 0, 0</td></tr>
        <tr><td>DEBOUNCE_WAIT</td><td>counter[2] == 1</td><td>WAIT</td><td>1, 0, 1</td></tr>
        <tr><td>DEBOUNCE_WAIT</td><td>otherwise</td><td>DEBOUNCE_WAIT</td><td>1, 0, 1</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3>Block Diagram</h3>
    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}images/labs/lab3/lab3_block.png`} alt="Block diagram" />
      <figcaption>Figure 3: Block diagram connecting all modules.</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h3>Schematic</h3>
    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}images/labs/lab3/lab3_schematic.png`} alt="Schematic" />
      <figcaption>Figure 4: FPGA schematic showing connections to dual 7-segment display and keypad.</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h2>Results and Discussion</h2>
    <p>
      The dual 7-segment display responds correctly to keypad inputs. Multiple simultaneous key presses register
      the first key only. Holding one key ignores all other inputs.
    </p>

    <h3>Testbench Simulation</h3>
    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}images/labs/lab3/mux_waveform.png`} alt="Mux waveform" />
    </figure>
    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}images/labs/lab3/mux_result.png`} alt="Mux results" />
      <figcaption>Figure 6: Mux module testbench — correct anode signals verified.</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}images/labs/lab3/seg_waveform.png`} alt="7-seg waveform" />
    </figure>
    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}images/labs/lab3/seg_results.png`} alt="7-seg results" />
      <figcaption>Figure 7: 7-segment display testbench results.</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}images/labs/lab3/scan_waves.png`} alt="Scanner waveform" />
      <figcaption>Figure 8: Scanner module — rows cycling to scan the keyboard.</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}images/labs/lab3/fsm_waves.png`} alt="FSM waveform" />
      <figcaption>Figure 9: FSM module — correct state transitions on column input.</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}images/labs/lab3/lab3_waves.png`} alt="Top module waveform" />
      <figcaption>Figure 10: Top-level module — all modules properly connected and toggling.</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h2>Conclusion</h2>
    <p>
      This lab took ~20 hours. Most time went to debugging keyboard hardware and the debouncing logic
      (I was registering multiple inputs when a key was held too long). One lesson: always verify keypad
      pinouts independently — the first keyboard pinout on the course website was incorrect.
    </p>

    <h2>AI Prototype Summary</h2>
    <p>
      I compared a monolithic prompt (all information at once) vs. modular prompts (broken into steps).
      The monolithic prompt generated a full design quickly but blurred module boundaries, produced synthesis
      errors, and required more debugging. Modular prompts gave cleaner FSMs, better readability, and made
      each piece easier to verify before integration. Key lesson: explicitly separate FSM responsibilities
      and clarify signal conventions upfront.
    </p>
  </section>
</LabLayout>
